<TEXT>
a woman who tried to fake her own 
death by using an unclaimed corpse from the morgue has been 
sentenced to two years in prison for falsely claiming a body 
among the many flaws investigators found in the scheme were the 
fact the defendant weighed 65 pounds less than the corpse and 
lacked its tattoos 
sandra p hall 35 who is halfway through a fouryear probation 
term for welfare fraud was sentenced thursday in los angeles 
county superior court for falsely obtaining an unclaimed body she 
had pleaded no contest to the charge 
her mother helen m tilch 59 of the los angeles suburb of san 
fernando has pleaded no contest to similar charges for helping ms 
hall in the scheme and faces a possible prison sentence 
deputy district attorney janice l maurizi contended the women 
concocted the scheme to elude probation officers and creditors ms 
hall who told authorities she got the idea from a television 
program said she was trying to escape from an abusive exhusband 
the people you are dealing with here have been involved in 
schemes all their lives said los angeles police detective 
stephen fisk 
ms hall who lives in tulare county and her mother obtained 
the remains of jane doe no 70 an unidentified partly decomposed 
body at the los angeles county coroners office 
identifying herself as sharon jt agee ms hall claimed that 
the corpse was her sister sharon p hall her mother backed up the 
story 
after having the body cremated they sent a copy of the death 
certificate to probation officials 
a probation officer reviewing the alleged death noticed the 
physical discrepancies while reading the autopsy report and 
contacted police jane doe no 70 weighed 195 pounds to ms halls 
130 and the corpse also had numerous tattoos 
further checks found the fingerprints from the body were 
different from ms halls 
