<TEXT>
engineers today sought the source of 
a small gas leak in a space shuttle steering engine a new problem 
nasa officials said could further delay the first shuttle flight 
since the challenger explosion 
experts were probing deep into discoverys left orbital 
maneuvering system engine pod in an effort to locate the leak but 
the leak was so tiny it was difficult to isolate and the process 
could take several days said nasa spokeswoman lisa malone 
launch pad workers detected an odor of nitrogen tetroxide gas 
friday while preparing discovery for its planned early september 
launch she said it was in a pod covering one of the two engines 
used to maneuver the shuttle in orbit 
nitrogen tetroxide serves as an oxidizer in the engines 
providing oxygen to ignite the fuel when the shuttle is in 
oxygenpoor space 
officials could not say whether the leak would further delay the 
launch already postponed several times since nasa set a liftoff 
date for last february malone said 
it will depend on where the leak is and how severe it is 
malone said 
officials said they believed the leak was in one of three 
places a power valve an oxidizer tank filter or a jet thruster 
if the leak is too inaccessible to be repaired on the pad 
malone said discovery might have to be returned to an assembly 
building a move officials estimated could delay the launch by 
several weeks 
when initially detected the leak rate was 15 parts per million 
considered very minor malone said the rate later dropped to 3 or 
4 ppm she said 
discovery is being readied for the first space shuttle flight 
since the challenger explosion that killed seven astronauts 2 
years ago 
elsewhere engineers at the morton thiokol plant in utah 
continue to inspect a solid fuel booster rocket damaged last week 
when a joint was mistakenly overpressurized 
a ground testfiring of the rocket has been delayed from late 
july until at least midaugust while experts consider what repairs 
have to be made 
the test the fifth fullscale firing of the redesigned rocket 
is considered essential before discovery can be committed to 
flight a faulty booster rocket joint triggered the challenger 
explosion 
</TEXT>
