an auto safety group says it will decide 
whether to appeal a court ruling that upholds a government decision 
letting automakers put off until 1993 a requirement for passive 
safety belts on a cars passenger side if the driver is protected 
by an air bag 
essentially what the court did is put passenger occupants of 
cars equipped with driverside air bags in a position of a 
likelihood of harm when the driver will walk away from the crash 
joan claybrook head of public citizen said friday 
the national highway traffic safety administration had agreed to 
a request by the ford motor co that allows continued use of 
manual safety belts on the passenger side in cars that have 
driverside air bags 
the highway safety agency in issuing the ruling last year agreed 
with auto industry claims that more time was needed to develop air 
bag systems for frontseat passengers 
public citizen a washingtonbased public interest group 
claimed that the ruling postpones passive restraint protection for 
car passengers for four years and puts them in additional danger 
the us court of appeals on friday upheld the nhtsa decision 
throwing out public citizens suit 
jeffrey miller deputy administrator of nhtsa called the court 
decision good news for consumers because air bags will now be 
available sooner and in more cars 
miller said the decision creates an incentive for automakers to 
make driverside air bags available while working on developing 
systems that protect both drivers and frontseat passengers 
