<DOCNO> AP880716-0130 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
william kennedy toiled over three novels during 
two decades of literary obscurity before no 4 the 
13timesrejected ironweed brought him a pulitzer prize and 
celebrity 
so perhaps he has earned the right to ham it up a bit in 
quinns book his latest novel 
set in the mid19th century quinns book viking 1895 
is the fourth in kennedys albany cycle of novels although daniel 
quinn the protagonist travels far afield of the city the author 
long ago staked out as his turf 
the book is a pastiche of writing styles from the period 
blending journalistic reportage dickensian melodrama and celtic 
folk tales 
quinn whom we first meet as a boatmans apprentice whose 
parents died of cholera begins his peripatetic adventures when he 
rescues a beautiful girl from drowning in the icy hudson while 
albany falls around him in a cataclysm of flood and fire by books 
end he is a celebrated journalist who earned his reputation 
covering the civil war along the way he witnesses the opening of 
the saratoga racetrack the draft riots in new york the workings 
of the underground railroad and other wonders more fantasy than 
fact 
in a recent interview kennedy explained how his albany cycle 
evolved 
its a conception that goes back to the 60s thats when i 
began to think about writing a book like quinn only much larger 
than quinn that would take the whole history of the city from 
the time of the patroons those who held large estates under grants 
from dutch government in new york up to contemporary times he 
said 
it was excessively ambitious so i started chopping the 
history into pieces eventually it evolved that i was going to 
do these connected novels i didnt know how many novels so i 
didnt want to say trilogy or quintet or anything like that so 
i just called it a cycle and this is another in the cycle 
he was asked if albany has become his yoknapatawpha county the 
fictional mississippi setting of so many of william faulkners 
works 
i would say so its a place where i can spread out and write 
about anything in american history and make it relevant to that 
particular part of the country but also to the country at large 
he said because albany is in a very real sense a microcosm of 
the whole country 
kennedy professed to idolizing faulkner 
hes the one person i regret not having met i think hes the 
greatest american writer of the 20th century his whole creation of 
yoknapatawpha was the reason i began to write this series of 
connected novels i found the way he interconnected his lives to be 
quite extraordinary and i thought it was a very compelling way to 
write 
fans of the other albany novels legs billy phelans 
greatest game and ironweed will enjoy ferreting out 
characters in quinns book mentioned as ancesters in those 
works quinn for example is the grandfather of 10yearold daniel 
quinn in ironweed 
unlike legs kennedys fictional rendering of the reallife 
gangster legs diamond the author didnt let himself get bogged 
down in historical research for quinns book 
i worked quite differently on this book he said i knew 
where i was going in a certain general sense i knew i wanted to 
deal with the civil war with journalism with the theater with 
conspiratorial secret societies and i knew some things about them 
so i went and did specific kinds of research the opening day at 
saratoga racetrack for example i went to some pains to be 
accurate 
during his research kennedy stumbled across the name will 
canaday which he found too irresistible to pass up so with tongue 
firmly in cheek the author himself a former newspaperman 
bestowed the name on a secondary character the editor of the 
albany chronicle who takes young quinn under his wing 
the success of ironweed has allowed kennedy 60 a longtime 
film buff to branch into writing screenplays he wrote the 
original screenplay for the francis coppoladirected the cotton 
club as well as the screen adaptation of ironweed he has 
also writen scripts for legs and billy phelan although 
neither is currently under production 
kennedy is asked how writing for the cinema differs from writing 
a novel 
very much different with a novel you can do anything with a 
screenplay your scenes have to play in a page and a half 
everything has to be created visually you cant go inside a 
characters mind the way you do in a novel you cant have 
people explaining things talking forever like you can do in a 
novel 
meanwhile kennedy said he has just begun work on a novel that 
is still too embryonic to discuss except that it is set in 1958 
and in albany of course 
</TEXT>
