<TEXT>
bedouin tribesmen wont go near the 
quicksands in the desert of northern oman they say caravans of 
camels and herds of goats have been swallowed up in what they call 
the umm assamim mother of poisons 
but western engineers are moving in just the same defying the 
desert nomads superstition in hopes of tapping natural gas 
believed to lie deep below the surface 
weve heard the stories and were obviously concerned said 
john hayhurst the british plant manager of desert line the omani 
company that is preparing to build a road and set up drilling rigs 
in the region 
you have to approach a project like this with infinite care 
you have to investigate every inch of land before you move 
bedouin tribes such as the nomadic duru know how to endure the 
sandstorms and blazing sun of the rub al khali empty quarter the 
great sandsea of arabia with its 600foothigh dunes 
but they will not venture near the quicksands in the belief they 
are haunted by devils 
bedouin tales speak of caravans of camels and their riders and 
herds of goats disappearing in the quicksands of oman which is in 
the southeastern corner of the arabian peninsula 
most of hayhursts workers are foreigners mainly from india and 
pakistan 
hayhurst said if workers wander off the compacted areas they 
could indeed sink without trace 
weve very nearly lost equipment he said were well 
equipped with ropes and chains 
hayhurst 39 is a 17year veteran of prospecting in the middle 
east and africa but this is his first experience with quicksands 
drillers will shortly move into the area just south of the 
yibal oilfield discovered in 1962 targeted under the omani 
governments gas exploration program directed by the staterun 
petroleum development oman pdo 
oil is the backbone of omans economy its production is about 
600000 barrels daily gas exploration is being intensified mainly 
for local consumption 
pdos project engineer dutchman jan martens said the 
surface is a salty silty material which is reasonably hard when 
dry but when wet is soft and would swallow a vehicle 
the sandy layer is nine meters 27 feet deep at the drilling 
locations 
his engineers will float a road across the quicksands to 
support a 1500ton drilling rig the road will be built from 
layers of webbed matting that will bind the soft sand together 
beneath compacted surface material 
the first european to observe these quicksands was the british 
explorer wilfred thesiger who described them in his book 
arabian sands 
the ground of white gypsum powder was covered with a sand 
sprinkled crust of salt through which protruded occasional dead 
twigs of salt bush he wrote 
these scattered bushes marked the firm land farther out only 
a slight darkening of the surface indicated the bog below 
his arab companion warned him not to go too near telling 
thesiger a raiding party of bedouin warriors had perished in the 
sands and that he himself had watched a flock of goats disappear 
the scientific explanation lies in the quicksands geographical 
position as omans lowest inland area just 177 feet above sealevel 
the area acts as a sump for rainwater running out from gulches 
in the mountains of northern oman 
as the water runs down it leaches salt from the earth and 
carries it to into the mother of poisons where the water 
evaporates in the searing sun crystallizing the salt in a thick 
white crust on the surface 
the crust crunches underfoot but its firmness is deceptive and 
the water table may be only a few inches underneath 
the sands were the center of a flourishing salt trade many years 
ago 
caravans of camels ventured in some never returned the bedouin 
say swallowed without trace 
</TEXT>
