<TEXT>
it hasnt happened since 1975 but some year the 
united states will once again export more than it imports the 
question is when 
the dollar leaped friday as currency traders decided the nation 
was making rapid progress toward wiping out the trade deficit the 
optimism was spawned by a government report that the may deficit 
was a relatively low 109 billion 
but currency traders are notoriously shortterm forecasters far 
more interested in the next tick of the dollaryen exchange rate 
than the outlook for trade in the 1990s 
and in a strange twist trade improvement is likely to be set 
back in the long run because of the very rise in the dollar that 
has come from expectations that trade will improve a higher dollar 
makes us products less competitive in world markets 
including fridays jump the dollar has ascended 9 percent 
against the west german mark and 7 percent against the japanese yen 
since june 10 
cautious american companies have just begun aggressively 
pursuing export opportunities made possible by the lower dollar 
and some could back off if they feel the dollars rise is going to 
last 
moreover foreign companies that were about to be dislodged from 
the us market might decide to hang on a bit longer because of the 
dollars rise 
for both those reasons its terribly important to keep the 
dollar down richard obrien of londonbased american express 
bank ltd said in a recent interview 
while mays deficit was the second smallest in nearly three 
years imports still exceeded exports by 41 percent small 
incremental changes cannot quickly wipe out a gap of that size 
some economists the optimists say the switch from red ink to 
black ink on the trade ledgers could happen on a monthly basis by 
late next year and on an annual basis by 1990 
our advantage is we can export literally thousands of 
products were not unidimensional said one of the optimists 
thomas carpenter vice president and director of economics for asb 
capital management in washington 
given the weak dollar we can sell anything from basic 
materials to agricultural products to boeing aircraft to 
automobiles and computer software products weve got it he said 
we will see the results and well see it in spades said 
charles reeder who runs a forecasting firm in wilmington del 
and says the benefits of the dollars longterm decline have been 
underestimated 
the economists spoke before the last leg of the dollars rise 
late this past week 
other economists say the first annual merchandise trade surplus 
will not come until nearly the end of the century because the 
torrid pace of export growth is bound to slow down 
exports will grow close to 7 percent annually over the next 
decade while imports grow about 2 percent a year predicts the wea 
group in bala cynwyd pa which predicts merchandise trade will 
not flip to a surplus until 1997 
the percentage differential between export and import growth 
just chews away at the surplus year by year said wefas glenn 
forman 
the vastly different forecasts for zero day the day when 
exports finally catch up with imports is a sign of the 
inexactitude of economics trade isnt measured by the day anyway 
picking the year is probably the best anyone can expect 
wefa group is one of the few organizations willing to make 
forecasts even tentative ones for a decade ahead 
theres definitely a limit to what we can reasonably 
project said stacy kottman of georgia states economic 
forecasting center which declines to make forecasts much past next 
year 
small unanticipated changes say if the dollar continues to 
rally then that will dampen the progress we make against the 
merchandise trade deficit he said 
the georgia state group predicts the trade deficit will still be 
averaging 8 billion to 9 billion a month next summer 
thrift is a virtue and trade surpluses would allow the nation 
to begin digging itself out of its status as the worlds biggest 
debtor but economists dont even agree whether it is important to 
vanquish the deficit or worry about debtor status 
i believe that the reasons for the trade deficit are much more 
fundamentally positive than many would have us believe said 
brian wesbury an economist for harris trust and savings bank in 
chicago 
wesbury argues the trade deficit is a byproduct of foreigners 
strong desire to invest in the united states americas high 
technology and rapid productivity growth make it an attractive 
place to sink money and foreigners are paying for their 
investments by shipping their goods here he said 
the more we move away from freemarket policies and a low tax 
environment the sooner well get to that zero situation but wed 
end up hurting our economy hurting productivy making this a less 
attractive place to invest wesbury said 
shrinking the deficit to zero may easily take another decade 
wesbury said and he is in no hurry to see it happen sooner 
even economists who are more concerned about the deficit dont 
think it will or should shrink too rapidly 
consider that most of the increase in shipments of manufactured 
goods has come from making better use of existing plants with 
factories churning near their full practical capacity and the labor 
market tightening exports cannot continue to expand rapidly 
without severe inflationary strains 
the market swings from overpessimism to excessive optimism we 
awkwardly find ourselves on the lets cool it folks side having 
been bulls on the side of an export boom obrien of american 
express bank said 
</TEXT>
